This document provides a single, unified technical summary of the development phases discussed for the Avatar Fight League (AFL) and ARC-LITE M1 launcher project. This includes the 16-player arena layout, replicated tennis ball launcher blueprints, and the global Material Parameter Collection (MPC) styling.

Phase 1: Arena Map Layout (16-Player Capacity)
For a high-intensity 16-player (8v8) "Assault" style arena in Unreal Engine 5, the design balances historical gauntlet mechanics with modern multiplayer requirements.

Dimensions: The recommended gameplay area is 150' x 300' (approx. 45m x 90m), expanding upon the traditional 85' x 200' event floor to prevent immediate spawn-killing.
Verticality: A height of 30' to 40' is required to accommodate elevated "Gladiator Pedestals" and the final "Wall" climb objective.
Landscape Settings: Use a 63x63 quads section size for optimal performance on mid-grade hardware.

Key Zones:
The Outer Ring: 5–7 geometric cover stations for attacking players.
The Pits: Low-ground hazard zones (trenches or balance beams).
Gladiator Pedestals: 10'–15' high vantage points for defenders using ARC-LITE M1 launchers. 

Phase 2: Replicated Tennis Ball Launcher (LED Ball) (ARC-LITE M1)
The launcher system uses server-authoritative logic to ensure all 16 players see the same projectiles simultaneously without significant network jitter. 

1. The Projectile (BP_TennisBall)
Collision: Sphere Collision set to BlockAllDynamic with Continuous Collision Detection (CCD) enabled to prevent high-speed phasing through thin arena walls.
Movement: Use the Projectile Movement Component with an Initial Speed of 3000–5000 and Gravity Scale of 0.2–0.5 for an authentic "floaty" feel.
Replication: In Class Defaults, check Replicates and Replicate Movement. 

2. The Firing Logic (BP_Launcher)
To handle rapid fire across 16 players, use a Timer-based approach instead of Tick events for performance. 

Client Input: When a player presses the fire button, it triggers a Server RPC (Run on Server, Reliable).
Server Authority: The server starts a looping timer (Set Timer by Event) that spawns the BP_TennisBall at the muzzle transform.
Client Release: When the player releases the button, another Server RPC clears the timer handle to stop firing. 

Phase 3: AFL Style Material Parameter Collection (MPC)
The AFL branding system utilizes a central MaterialParameterCollection (MPC) to synchronize visual states (LED colors, branding, hazards) across the entire arena globally without recompiling shaders. 

MPC Naming: Follow the convention MPC_AFL_GlobalParams.
Vector Parameters:
Team_Primary_Color: Global tint for team-based LED strips on launchers and robot armor.
Sponsor_Tint: Changes global branding accents (e.g., Penske, UniTree, Google, Fanatics) across all arena textures instantly.

Scalar Parameters:
LED_Pulse_Intensity: Drives the brightness of the glowing tennis balls and launcher strips.
Arena_Hazard_Glow: Controls the emissive power of "Kill Zone" floor markers.

Application: Use the CollectionParameter node in any material to reference these global values. When the value is changed in the MPC, every material using it updates dynamically in real-time across all 16 client instances. 
